  <subsection xml:id="review-trig-6">
    <title>Trig Equations</title>
    
    <remark>
      <p>
        When solving equations involving trigonometric functions, the process is similar to solving polynomial functions; however, three things must be kept in mind:
        <ul>
          <li>
            <p>
              A trigonometric function <alert>must</alert> be of the form <m>\text{trig }(x)</m>
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The range of the function in question
            </p>
          </li>
          <li>
            <p>
              The interval(s) involved in the question
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </p>
    </remark>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the equation <m>\cos^2(x) - 2\cos (x) + 1 = 0</m>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          <m>x = 0</m> is the base solution, but because <m>\cos (x)</m> has period <m>2\pi</m>, the solution set is
          <me>
            x = 2\pi k,\, k\in \Z
          </me>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>

    <example>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Solve the equation <m>\sin (3x) = \dfrac{1}{2}</m> on the interval <m>[0,2\pi)</m> and in general.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          On the interval <m>[0,2\pi)</m>, the solutions are
          <me>
            x = \dfrac{\pi}{18}, \dfrac{13\pi}{18}, \dfrac{25\pi}{18}
          </me>
          and 
          <me>
            x = \dfrac{5\pi}{18}, \dfrac{17\pi}{18}, \dfrac{29\pi}{18}
          </me>
        </p>
        <p>
          The general solutions are
          <me>
            x = \dfrac{\pi}{18} + \dfrac{2\pi}{3}k
          </me>
          and
          <me>
            x = \dfrac{5\pi}{18} + \dfrac{2\pi}{3}k
          </me>
          where <m>k\in \Z</m>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </example>
  </subsection>
